-- Hong Kong shares rise, Lenovo at near 14-year high
-- By Clement Tan
-- Wed Jan 15, 2014 03:10AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Jan 15 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares rose on Wednesday as Chinese PC maker Lenovo Group surged to its highest close in nearly 14 years, extending strong gains after reports suggested it bucked a broader decline in PC shipments last quarter.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended up 0.5 percent at 22,902 points, with trade locked in the same 320-point range it has been in for nearly two weeks. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the top offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong also rose 0.5 percent. [ID:nL3N0KP100] Gains came in sluggish turnover largely focused on a few sectors, including Chinese cement producers and sportswear brands after a series of profit alerts and warnings. Anhui Conch Cement <0914.HK> and China Resources Cement <1313.HK> rose about 6 percent after issuing positive profit alerts, spurring some short covering that lifted all cement producers. [ID:nL3N0KO2HN][ID:nWNBS00A1X] 361 Degrees <1361.HK> plummeted 6.5 percent in its biggest loss in seven months after warning 2013 net profit will be "significantly lower" than the year before, weighing on sector peers. Li Ning <2331.HK> sank 4 percent. [ID:nWNBS00A29]